>>114464997
desu you really have to know how to play the drums to program drums that sound real.

But If you just want less robotic sounding, it’s all about syncopation. Syncopation makes the rhythm. You can have the most robotic on-the-grid kick, snare and hats, but when you add another perc sound that accents an off beat in one of the measures, it fixes it and sounds human. The breakbeat sample on top works because it has syncopation in the pattern.

And to preemptively clarify what I mean by accenting the off beats. It’s the extra kick drum hits just before the end of the phrase. It’s the extra snare hit before or after the 2s and 4s. It’s the Tom hit when every other perc is on a rest.

Good tune btw

My take on the matter:
I just did some heavy leads tone test on top of this Youtube heavy track https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTPADCjSIcE

No mixing or processing involved, just pure sound of ZOOM DSP into CAB sims in DAW. It cuts right through the track. This unit is a digital signal processor, but it has a analog valve single tube for preamp stage for some gain saturation.

https://vocaroo.com/1aoJxs7V9i7N

Even though this unit is 30 years old, it is still better in "cutting through" any heavy distorted mix than even some of the NEURAL DSP sim stuff I have tried that use pure guitar signal without any analog stages before the DAW. And this is without any post-EQ or mixing.

Literally just get some old hardware, these units sell for about 100-120 dollars used, the avg. you would spend on some shitty Amp sim with 1000 features and they all sound mediocre and always require shit ton of mixing, EQ and fucking around. Everything else, IRs, Power Amp sims, can be found for free.

One piece of easy, cheap-as-free advice is to envision what a physical setup would be and think about how to recreate digitally. So, for example, if you had a plex turned to 11 you'd stick a sm57 in the sweet spot and a 121 in the middle maybe. Well, that would mean taking two copies of the same guitar wav with the same amp and cab sims and treating them different in terms of eq. You're not pushing real air against a Mic but you can bus both of those to a separate reverb channel and keep bringing it up in the mix a cunt hair at a time until it's Just barely audible.

>>114480708
lol this is the hard way to make a melody.

some people start here. or some people figure out major/minor scales modes etc and try to use those to make melodies.. but again it's too many notes in my opinion to easily make a good melody.

Simplify it down to the pentatonic scale OR a six note scale. By six note scale, I mean like the major scale with the fourth removed, or a minor scale without the 6th.
It helps if you can improvise around these scales too.
Most melodies are really simple and only use these notes.
Going up and down scales is a good way to make amateur sounding melodies. Leave some notes out, the ones that don't sound that good, just play the notes that sound good. Easy.

Should I make a youtube video about this with a basedface caption called the SECRET METHOD to melody making the pros don't want you to know?

>>114491706
its a bit free form and it depends on what you want to make
Like if I want to make a bell then I might start with filter envelopes first to get the base of sound down and then get to messing around with EQ/distortion for harmonics and adding reverb or delay at the end to make it sound dreamy and complete
If i want something like a reese bass then I might start with the wave shaping first and then modulating different filters after
Once you understand the basics and you've listened to enough music you get an ear for hearing what and how sounds are made up of, Most sounds you'll hear are made with some type of gimmick or technique, they're usually not some super complex engineering other than a few niche EDM genres like hardstyle kicks or neurobass leads/basses

>>114496636
These are their albums worth checking out

>Killing Technology
Proggy thrash metal
>Dimension Hatross
Thrashy prog metal, less emphasis on the thrash. Probably their proggiest album.
>Nothingface
Progressive metal with a pretty unique post-punk edge, not so much thrash metal
>The Outer Limits
Pretty solid prog metal with a clear early 90s alternative rock sound. Jack Luminous is their best song.
>The Wake
Surprisingly great return to form to their Dimension Hatross sound after 25 years of mediocrity

Their first two albums aren't prog.
Angel Rat's a weird alternative rock/metal album, some people like it but it's not prog.
Negatron is their obligatory 1990s 80s-thrash-metal-band-gone-butt-metal album but with Voivod's signature angular dissonant riffing style.
Phobos is Negatron but more spaced out and proggy, might be worth listening to if you don't mind 90s butt metal.

Literally everything Voivod's put out in the 2000s and early 2010s has been unremarkable until The Wake.

I’m an expert on Loveless. It’s a good album. Not as good as let’s say Jimi Hendrix but it’s a pass in my book. Nor the Beatles. However, I’m not here for some pointless bashing (except the vocabulary kind).

This song is the best on the album and my favourite. It’s like hypnosis. Sometimes, I think the violin sounds very industrial, like an alarm, but the rest of the song is blissful. It’s like a really deep pink sunset that you’re watching with a girl you’re gonna break up with (and already have broken up with in your mind). The guitar riff is a floating pink river. It’s very warm in there. It’s love, too. In the live version I noticed for the first time the chemistry in the guitars. If you listen very closely, there are two guitar lines, along with the violin. It’s cool. The effect is really big. It’s like a well-performed love scene, with guitars.

Now I’m listening to Only Shallow and the difference is apparent, like two awkward bumbling teenagers play-fighting with their shoulders while they walk together on a calm winter night.

The second half of the album is really the better half. Only Shallow is good, Loom is underwhelming at best (but I’m always searching for a reason to like it - maybe the lyrics, because they stand out a lot more in that song than the lyrics of the rest of the album, and when I try to remember anything from the song, it’s that line little girls and their party dresses — but WHO CARES when they could listen to Soon. That’s the song that showed me this album is almost approaching a dance album. Every beat is static. It’s like house music. That really puts it closer in style to Bowery Electric than Slowdive, at least from the albums I’ve heard by Slowdive. I heard tell of them going in electronic directions.

>>114488500
>sorry i was under the impression that drastically changing the tuning (say, to a c standard) means having to alter stuff like the nut or something in adition to using thicker strings
The reason people use thicker strings when they downtune a step or more is the strings get really floppy and can create fret buzz. If you're using a set of 9's in D standard with action around .4mm on treble and .5mm on bass side, it's not going to work. You'll have to raise the action. I have a guitar that lives in D standard/C# with a full floating Floyd for that reason. A good middle ground CAN be using 10's if you don't go below D.

And here are my thoughts:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HgqOvEQdU0E

Here is for example a blind test done on many people who could not tell difference between a real Real Mic'ed Cab VS IR (Impulse Response). The other one was a real recording with real mics, loud decibels, the other one was with amps and a silent recording you could do with your headphones on. Most of the commenters could not tell the difference between reveal.

>I'm about to purchase my first amp and I'm wondering does it really make any sense for me to get a cheap amp over an audio interface. I'll be only really able to practice in the late evenings so I'll be on my headphones for most of the time anyways.

So what is your budget? If you don't play gigs or rehearse with a real band with loud instruments like drums you are competing etc. I would not get a real amp. If your budget is $500, I would spent it literally on some quality IR pack (York Audio, Ownhammer etc. around $20), Focusrite Scarlett Solo and rest of the money I would buy some sort of used real preamp unit for $200-300 bucks. You could then drive this to your DAW of choice and use power amp sims (TPA-1 is free) and mix it with IRs and you could get great studio quality tones, totally silently, any time of the day.

Also, like the MP-1, the Rolls had two independent gain controls, one for each stage, and a built-in chorus. Despite its similarity to the ADA, the Rolls MP-45 sounds a bit different. The character of the sound is much closer to the Marshall JMP-1 in terms of distortion, gain. The dimensions of the MP-45 are the same as the ADA including depth.

ADA MP-1 seems to sell for like 900-1000$ these days per unit. You can still get these Rolls units for like $100-200. Can honestly recommend this if you like ADA MP-1 or MP-2.

>>114490931
The most frustrating thing about learning to play music is how slow progress can feel. Everyone picks up an instrument expecting to be able to play a song almost right away. The first time I played bass, I played until my fingers bled. I told myself "I have to push through this and build the strength in my left hand" but by the end of it, it hurt so bad I didn't pick up my bass or my guitar for a while. Don't overdo it. Practice every day, but don't feel the need to do a LOT of practice every day your first few weeks. It's better to practice a little bit every day than to practice a lot once or twice a week.

You've gotta accept that it's something you'll slowly be chipping away at for a long time or you're ngmi.

>>114499294
NTA. The new Epiphones are made in Indonesia and China. The older ones were made in Korea. The Korean ones usually used nicer wood and had better overall build quality. The new ones have better sounding pickups (accidentally) and the Epiphone P90s are actually indistinguishable from the Gibson ones. Some of the higher end ones use CTS pots. The downside with the new ones is that they're made of worse quality wood. Note all the "repaired" husks on Ebay and Reverb. They also have much shitter QC.
The Indonesian Kramers/Epiphones are the ones to go for if you're buying new. Kramers are a better buy if you're a /meal/fag because you get Seymour Duncan pickups. You also get a decent maple neck vs whatever hotdog wood they call mahogany for Epiphone necks. When they're good, they're REALLY good. Just buy somewhere with a good return policy because of the QC problems. If it says "Handcrafted" in China, steer clear.

posts.com: is there an easy way to transcribe music to midis? I want to do some bone thugs songs including the vocals but it seems like the vocals in particular are pretty complicated rhythmically so is there an easy way to do it with software nowadays? I don't care if it comes out looking like a mess with whacky time signatures and 32nd rests and stuff (it most likely will) as long as it plays... also don't care about like instrument voicing or whatever. Just rhythm and notes is all I want

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114502854
You'd have to separate the audio into stems using software like spleeter.online (free) or ozone rx (paid). Then convert the stems into midi, using something like ableton live (paid) or melodyne (paid).
This will result in a midi that still requires a lot of manual cleanup.

Your best bet is probably to transcribe it manually, which at least is good ear training. Also check whosampled.com for the original samples.

You don't really need to know the formal language to express what you mean when you can just play it or reference something specific that already exists for example instead of knowing a ghost note is called a ghost note you can just reference someone known for it like Rocco Prestia or play it yourself because you've identified it as a specific kind of note.

He was the band's original drummer, and the younger brother of BTO's namesake founder Randy Bachman.

>Robbie Bachman, founding drummer of Bachman-Turner Overdrive, has died at the age of 69...

>The Bachman brothers grew up playing together in their Winnipeg, Canada home and became natural collaborators. It was Randy who gave Robbie his first job, enlisting the drummer to join him and bassist Fred Turner in the band Brave Belt in 1971. A third Bachman, guitarist Tim, joined Brave Belt a year later.

>After two unsuccessful albums, Brave Belt was dropped by their label. Undeterred, the band searched for a new home. At the suggestion of management, theybegan calling themselves Bachman–Turner Overdrive.

>The same band but with a new name, Bachman–Turner Overdrive released their self-titled debut in 1973. Commercial success continued to elude the group, but later that year they released a second LP, Bachman–Turner Overdrive II. That album featured BTO's first Top 40 single, "Let It Ride," which peaked at No. 23 on the Billboard Hot 100. The album's second single would rocket the group to stardom: “Takin' Care of Business.”

>The hits kept on coming for BTO, as their third album, 1974’s Not Fragile, reached No. 1 in the U.S. “You Ain’t Seen Nothing Yet” became a massive, chart-topping hit, while follow-up single “Roll On Down the Highway” continued the band’s run of success. The latter track was co-written by Robbie, one of a handful of classic tunes he helped pen.
